   </facsimile>
   <standOff>
      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_681" type="description">
            <term id="misc_681-term">It has often happened during the</term>
            <gloss id="misc_681-gloss" target="#misc_681-term">
               <p>This lecture was given on 28 February 1805, 2pm and repeated on 29 January 1806 and 6 April 1808; it is published in Humphry Davy on Geology: the 1805 Lectures for the General Audience, ed. Robert Siegfried and Robert H. Dott, Jnr (University of Wisconsin Press, 1980), pp. 10-21. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_855" type="description">
            <term id="misc_855-term">Toadstone</term>
            <gloss id="misc_855-gloss" target="#misc_855-term">
               <p>Regional name for a type of igneous rock found between layers of limestone rock in Derbyshire, England. John Whitehurst wrote about it in his 1778 Enquiry into the Original State and Formation of the Earth, suggesting that the rock was igneous rather than sedimentary.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_853" type="description">
            <term id="misc_853-term">Antediluvian</term>
            <gloss id="misc_853-gloss" target="#misc_853-term">
               <p>A term which refers to the period of time described in the Bible between the fall of humankind and the flood (Genesis). </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_100" type="description">
            <term id="misc_100-term">Plutonic Theory</term>
            <gloss id="misc_100-gloss" target="#misc_100-term">
               <p>Relates to the Plutonist theories of James Hutton (1715-1795), who proposed that the earth's igneous rocks were formed from magma. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_588" type="description">
            <term id="misc_588-term">Neptunian Theory</term>
            <gloss id="misc_588-gloss" target="#misc_588-term">
               <p>A theory of geology proposed by Abraham Gottlob Werner, who proposed that rocks formed from the crystallisation of minerals in the early Earth's oceans.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_560" type="description">
            <term id="misc_560-term">Neptune</term>
            <gloss id="misc_560-gloss" target="#misc_560-term">
               <p>The Roman god of freshwater and the sea in Roman religion.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_783" type="description">
            <term id="misc_783-term">Serapis</term>
            <gloss id="misc_783-gloss" target="#misc_783-term">
               <p>Serapis or Sarapis is a Graeco-Egyptian god. A syncretic deity derived from the worship of the Egyptian Osiris and Apis, Serapis was extensively popularized in the third century BC on the orders of Greek Pharaoh Ptolemy I Soter, as a means to unify the Greek and Egyptian subjects of the Ptolemaic Kingdom.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
      </listAnnotation>
      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_266">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de</forename>
               <surname>Buffon</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1707"/>
            <death when="1788"/>
            <note>French naturalist, mathematician and cosmologist. His Histoire Naturelle, published in 1789, ran to 37 volumes. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_866">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Benoit</forename>
               <surname>de Maillet</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1656"/>
            <death when="1738"/>
            <note>French natural philosopher who presented controversial evolutionary speculations.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_906">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Leucippus</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c.480 BCE"/>
            <death when="c.420 BCE"/>
            <note>a pre-Socratic Greek philosopher. He is traditionally credited as the founder of atomism, which he developed with his student Democritus. Leucippus divided the world into two entities: atoms, indivisible particles that make up all things, and the void, the nothingness that exists between the atoms.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_505">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Edmond</forename>
               <surname>Halley</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1656"/>
            <death when="1742"/>
            <note>Astronomer and natural philosopher, who, using Newtonian mechanics, predicted the return of what became the eponymous comet. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_246">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Robert</forename>
               <surname>Hooke</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1635"/>
            <death when="1703"/>
            <note>Natural philosopher who acted as experimental demonstrator at the Royal Society of London during its early years. Prominent in the study of air and microscopy amongst other subjects. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_039">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">John</forename>
               <surname>Woodward</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1665"/>
            <death when="1728"/>
            <note>Natural philospher with an interest in geology. His collection of fossils and minerals is part of Cambridge University's Sedgwick Museum of Geology. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1000">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">John</forename>
               <surname>Whitehurst</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1713"/>
            <death when="1788"/>
            <note>a clockmaker and scientist who made significant early contributions to geology and was an influential member of the Lunar Society. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_026">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Henry</forename>
               <surname>Cavendish</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1731"/>
            <death when="1810"/>
            <note>A central figure in English natural philosophy and chemistry, among other research he determined the density of the earth and discovered what would later be named hydrogen. He was one of the people who helped appoint Davy to the Royal Institution. Following his death in 1810 Davy delivered a widely-quoted eulogy on Cavendish and later arranged for some of his apparatus to be transferred to the Royal Institution. FRSL. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_016">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Joseph</forename>
               <surname>Priestley</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1804"/>
            <note>Unitarian and political radical forced into exile in Pennsylvania. As a natural philospher and chemist who retained belief in phlogiston, he discovered oxygen and nitrous oxide though not under those names. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_033">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Torbern Olaf</forename>
               <surname>Bergman</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1735"/>
            <death when="1784"/>
            <note>Swedish chemist and mineralogist. At some point Davy acquired a set of letters from Bergman to Franz Schwediaur written in the 1780s which are retained in the Royal Institution (RI MS HD/27/A). ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_036">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Isaac</forename>
               <surname>Newton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1642"/>
            <death when="1727"/>
            <note>Prominent English natural philosopher and mathematician greatly admired by Davy who once under the influence of several litres of nitrous oxide wrote in his notebook 'Davy &amp; Newton' in one inch letters. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_520">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Jean-André</forename>
               <surname>Deluc</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1727"/>
            <death when="1817"/>
            <note>Swiss-born geologist, natural philosopher and meteorologist who spent much of his time working in England. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1063">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Johan Gottschalk</forename>
               <surname>Wallerius</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1709"/>
            <death when="1785"/>
            <note>A Swedish chemist and mineralogist. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_247">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Carl</forename>
               <surname>Linnaeus</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1707"/>
            <death when="1778"/>
            <note>Professor of Physic and Botany at Uppsala University. Developed the modern system of taxonomic classification. ForMemFRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_151">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Edward Charles</forename>
               <surname>Howard</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1774"/>
            <death when="1816"/>
            <note>A brother of the Duke of Norfolk, he became a chemist, discovering the explosive properties of mercury fulminate. FRSL</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_303">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antonio-Lazzaro</forename>
               <surname>Moro</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1687"/>
            <death when="1764"/>
            <note>Italian abbot, naturalist and geologist.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_125">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">James</forename>
               <surname>Hutton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1726"/>
            <death when="1797"/>
            <note>Scottish geologist, agriculturalist and chemical manufacturer. His Theory of the Earth (1795) is one of the foundations of modern geology. Davy discussed Hutton's theories in his lectures and visited some of the key geological sites that Hutton used in his work. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_267">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Abraham Gottlob</forename>
               <surname>Werner</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1749"/>
            <death when="1817"/>
            <note>German geologist who proposed the theory of Neptunism and who also proposed the chronological sequence found in stratified rocks.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_023">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Richard</forename>
               <surname>Kirwan</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1812"/>
            <note>Irish chemist, mineralogist and geologist who accused fellow geologist, James Hutton, of athiesm following publication of his Theory of the Earth (1788). FRSL</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_263">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Pluto</surname>
            </persName>
            <note>The ruler of the underworld in ancient Greek mythology and religion.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_164">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">James</forename>
               <surname>Hall</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1761"/>
            <death when="1832"/>
            <note>Scottish baronet (1776) and MP. Chemist and geologist who supported of James Hutton's theories of uniformitarian geology. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_1064">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Clement</forename>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c.150"/>
            <death when="c.215"/>
            <note>Clement of Alexandria was a Christian theologian and philosopher </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_162">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">John</forename>
               <surname>Playfair</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1819"/>
            <note>Professor of Natural Philosophy at Edinburgh University. His Illustrations of the Huttonian Theory of the Earth (1802) gave strong support to James Hutton's theory of uniformitarianism. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
