      <listPlace>
         <place xml:id="place_1094">
            <placeName>Cairo</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">30.054993719102942,  31.482410976965099</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Cairo is the capital of Egypt</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1191">
            <placeName>Mediterranean Sea</placeName>
            <note>Connected to the Atlantic Ocean and almost completely surrounded by land.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_085">
            <placeName>Derbyshire</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">52.921826207569474, -1.4773493148619199</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Derbyshire is a county in the East Midlands and includes part of the Peak District.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_184">
            <placeName>Mount Etna</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">37.751123181461516,  14.9934134370738</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Mount Etna, or simply Etna, is an active stratovolcano on the east coast of Sicily, Italy.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_492">
            <placeName>Derby</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">52.921826207569474, -1.4773493148619199</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Derby is an English city on the banks of the River Derwent in Derbyshire.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_198">
            <placeName>Switzerland</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">46.96573205519196, 8.3202673078412506</geo>
            </location>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_247">
            <placeName>Alps </placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">46.91855850327627,  9.6255793068951494</geo>
            </location>
            <note>The Alps are the highest and most extensive mountain range that lies entirely in Europe. They are located in eight European countries.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_324">
            <placeName>Germany</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">51.189579071880495,  10.618914269201101</geo>
            </location>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_897">
            <placeName>France</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">46.66388672376419,  2.6130755071286602</geo>
            </location>
            <note>France, officially the French Republic, is a country located primarily in Western Europe.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_121">
            <placeName>England</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">52.12544136722214, -1.7566152421063299</geo>
            </location>
            <note>England is a country that is part of the United Kingdom. It is located on the island of Great Britain, of which it covers approximately 62%, and over 100 smaller adjacent islands.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_226">
            <placeName>Geneva</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">46.20417523220347,  6.1425237890904398</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Geneva is a city in Switzerland on the border with France.</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_991">
            <placeName>Freiberg</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">50.918344283396074,  13.341167619912399</geo>
            </location>
            <note>A university and former mining town in Saxony, Germany</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_475">
            <placeName>Egypt</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">26.847302350713047,  29.800177329364502</geo>
            </location>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_1316">
            <placeName>Stonehenge</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">51.17961974045531,  -1.8262054509232</geo>
            </location>
            <note>a prehistoric megalithic structure on Salisbury Plain in Wiltshire, England</note>
         </place>
         <place xml:id="place_284">
            <placeName>Edinburgh</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">55.952743168058966,  -3.1904042104473902</geo>
            </location>
            <note>The capital city of Scotland.</note>
         </place>
      </listPlace>
      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_088">
            <form>sandstone</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sedimentary rock consisting of sand or quartz grains cemented together, typically red, yellow, or brown in colour.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_398">
            <form>slate </form>
            <def>
               <p>Slate is a fine-grained, foliated, homogeneous, metamorphic rock derived from an original shale-type sedimentary rock composed of clay or volcanic ash through low-grade, regional metamorphism</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_090">
            <form>limestone</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sedimentary rock composed mainly of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_105">
            <form>basalt</form>
            <def>
               <p>A dark grey to black dense to fine-grained igneous rock that consists of basic plagioclase, augite, and usually magnetite. More than 90% of volcanic rock on earth is basaltic.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_092">
            <form>granite</form>
            <def>
               <p>A coarse-grained intrusive igneous rock.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_058">
            <form>carbonic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CO2 or H2CO3 </p>
               <p>Now known as Carbon dioxide (CO2), or a solution of carbon dioxide in water (H2CO3). </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_078">
            <form>elastic fluid</form>
            <def>
               <p>A descriptive term for a gas, emphasising its elastic quality of spontaneous expansion.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
   </standOff>
   <text>
      <body xml:lang="en">
         <div>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="1"
                xml:id="pb-1"
                facs="#i1"/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology Lecture 4 1805</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#misc_681"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag1">
          It has often happened during the
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
progress of science that two doctrines<lb/>
immediately opposite have been supposed<lb/>
with great powers of reasoning and almost<lb/>
with equal plausibility<lb/>
Such a circumstance however almost<lb/>
always marks the infancy of the<lb/>
study and the imperfection of the<lb/>
methods of investigation .<lb/>
It proves that speculation has been<lb/>
merely employed <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">or</del> or partial<lb/>
facts only examined.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
And the Philosophical enquirer in<lb/>
opposing supposition to supposition<lb/>
and error to error will instantly percieve<lb/>
the insufficiency of either class of<lb/>
opinions: and will thus preserve<lb/>
the mind free from doubt from the<lb/>
prejudice of false systems from mistakes<lb/>
and confusion.-<lb/>
This method may be sometimes<lb/>
applied with <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">great</add> success in the examination<lb/>
of Geological Theories.<lb/>
It removes the necessity of strict<lb/>
discussion and it often devellopes<lb/>
absurdity without the assistance<lb/>
of<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough"> labour</del> laborious logical deductions<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> in his theory of the Globe<lb/>
supports that the surface is constantly<lb/>
becoming colder<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="person">
          M de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> on the other hand conceives<lb/>
that it is daily growing warmer<lb/>
The first attempts to prove that ice<lb/>
in the course of ages will extend even<lb/>
to the countries under the trop<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">p</del>ics<lb/>
Whilst the last conceives that in no<lb/>
very distant period it will disappear<lb/>
even from the poles<lb/>
The one Author fears unless the energies<lb/>
of the Sun are capable of opposing<lb/>
the laws of nature our cultivated<lb/>
lands will become snow clad plains<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
And the other dreads their conversion into<lb/>
burning deserts of sand, incapable of <lb/>
supporting vegetable life -<lb/>
It is scarcely possible to imagine two<lb/>
hypotheses in more perfect opposition; both<lb/>
have been defended with ingenuity both<lb/>
are founded upon mistakes -<lb/>
The one may be ballanced against the<lb/>
other there will be scarcely a perceptible<lb/>
difference in their weight and importance<lb/>
and they may be safely be given up together.<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">work</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> on Geology<lb/>
is called <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#otherwork_321"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag5">
                  <hi rend="underline">Telliamed</hi>
               </bibl>
            </rs> which is an anagram<lb/>
of his name a translation of it appeared<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
in English in 1750 -<lb/>
The Author professes to devellope the<lb/>
opinions of an indian philosopher whom<lb/>
he had met at <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_1094"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
          Cairo
        </name>
            </rs> when the Consul<lb/>
General of France was in that City.<lb/>
Though he intended to produce a<lb/>
philosophical Theory He has given it<lb/>
in the form of a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Romance</hi> for the<lb/>
fables are more numerous than the facts<lb/>
and it affords much entertainment<lb/>
but little or no instruction.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> from having observed an<lb/>
increase of Land on several parts of<lb/>
the coast of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_1191"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          mediterranean
        </name>
            </rs> conceives<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
that there must be an uniform law of<lb/>
diminution of the Sea in consequence<lb/>
of which the whole surface must at<lb/>
length become dry land.<lb/>
His opinion is very similar to that<lb/>
ancient one of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#person_906"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag9" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Leucippus</hi>.
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
And he farther supposes that the whole<lb/>
of the Globe in Early ages was covered<lb/>
with water: and that from the slow<lb/>
and gradual disappearance of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Ocean</hi>
            <lb/>
our present islands and continents<lb/>
have been formed and the existing<lb/>
order of things produced -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
I have mentioned this hypothesis because<lb/>
it is the foundation of the idea of the<lb/>
gradually increasing temperature of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Land</hi>. For <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> justly conceives<lb/>
that if water disappears Fire must accumulate<lb/>
and that the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dry surface</hi> must soon become<lb/>
inhabitable.<lb/>
All his observation of facts however are<lb/>
partial and his notion of the dissipation<lb/>
of the moisture of our globe into space<lb/>
shows a total ignorance of the laws of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">evaporation</hi> which long before the<lb/>
time of the publication of his work<lb/>
had been fully <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">develop</del> develloped<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#person_505"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag11" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hally.-
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
This excellent Philosopher has proved from<lb/>
the most accurate data that the fluid<lb/>
raised from the ocean and the surface of<lb/>
the Earth in consequence of the solar<lb/>
heat is condensed by cold in the upper<lb/>
regions of the air and that from its<lb/>
deposition clouds are produced and dew<lb/>
and rain which water the Earth and<lb/>
support vegetable <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">life</del> and animal life<lb/>
and form rivers that return the<lb/>
superfluous moisture into the sea<lb/>
its <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parent source</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
According to this beautiful system the foundations<lb/>
of which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">are distinct truths</hi> there is a<lb/>
constant circulation of moisture upon our Globe.<lb/>
No portion rises above the atmosphere<lb/>
no portion is lost: and amidst a variety of<lb/>
combinations and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">decompositions</hi>, the equilibrium<lb/>
is preserved  the quantity is unimpaired: and<lb/>
there is a constant application of it to the<lb/>
uses of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">living beings</hi>.-<lb/>
Most of the important errors of the early<lb/>
Geological systems of the moderns may indeed<lb/>
be referred to a want of acquaintance in<lb/>
their Authors with the great facts blonging<lb/>
to the order of Nature: and to an<lb/>
ignorance of the real essence of the<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">subterraneans</del> subterranean <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Kingdom</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
|_<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi> and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minerology</hi> till the<lb/>
middle of the last century were merely<lb/>
in the embryon state without order or<lb/>
beauty:<lb/>
And they offer the only true and permanent<lb/>
foundations on which a given Theory<lb/>
of the Earth can be erected.<lb/>
Not even the genius of a becker or a<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag12" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> not even the minutely enquiring<lb/>
spirit of a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#person_039"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
          Woodward
        </name>
            </rs> nor the imagination<lb/>
of a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag14" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> could supply the want of<lb/>
and extended system of experimental<lb/>
Knowledge.<lb/>
And it was not till chemical<lb/>
analysis had discovered the real composition<lb/>
And it was not till chemical<lb/>
an extended system of experimental<lb/>
analysis had discovered the real composition<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
of mineral bodies and given accuracy<lb/>
to the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">systems</hi> of Classification,<lb/>
It was not till this period that the<lb/>
changes taking place in the surface of<lb/>
the Globe in the present time could<lb/>
be accurately ascertained or any true<lb/>
analogical evidences gained of the<lb/>
intimate nature of the revolutions which<lb/>
had occurred in past ages.-<lb/>
One of the first persons who endeavored<lb/>
to employ real mineralogical and chemical<lb/>
knowledge in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">solution</hi> of the most<lb/>
remarkable appearances of the surface of the<lb/>
Globe was the late <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#person_1000"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Whitehurst.
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
His enquiry into the state and formation<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#otherwork_322"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag16">
            of the earth was published in 1778,
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
about the period when some of the most<lb/>
brilliant discoveries ever made with regard<lb/>
to intimate Nature of bodies were brought<lb/>
to light by D<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi> Black <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#person_026"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag17" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Cavendish
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#person_016"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag18" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Priestly
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#person_033"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Bergman.
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
Whitehurst was evidently <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">gifted</hi> with<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">an indefatigable spirit of investigation</hi>
            <lb/>
similar to that which actuated those<lb/>
celebrated men: and his labours though<lb/>
directed toward objects much more obscure<lb/>
and more difficultly attainable have<lb/>
have been highly meritorious and<lb/>
productive of important results.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
Whitehurst passed the early part of his life<lb/>
in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#place_085"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag20" type="place">
          Derbyshire
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
And it was from an observation of the<lb/>
many interesting phenomena of the<lb/>
mineral kingdom which occur upon a<lb/>
great scale in that County that he was<lb/>
first induced to direct his attention to<lb/>
Geology not so much as He himself informs<lb/>
us with a view of constructing a Theory<lb/>
as with the hope of obtaining such<lb/>
a competent knowledge of subterraneous<lb/>
Geography as might be applicable to<lb/>
useful purpose and to discoveries in<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Mining</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
His attention was however soon arested<lb/>
by a fact which it was scarcely<lb/>
possible for an active mind to notice<lb/>
without indulging in speculation<lb/>
without reasoning from effects concerning<lb/>
causes.-<lb/>
The principal strata in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#place_085"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag21" type="place">
          Derbyshire
        </name>
            </rs> are<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag22">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#chemical_398"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag23">
          slate
          
        </term>
            </rs> coal and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag24">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs> in some cases<lb/>
they are parallel to the horizon and regular in<lb/>
their disposition. but in other cases they are<lb/>
considerably broken and inclined.<lb/>
In some districts of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">conty</del>county<lb/>
a substance is found called by the Miners<lb/>
toad stone which is in fact a species of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#chemical_105"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag25">
          Basalt
          
        </term>
            </rs> and where this Rock occurs in<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
The greatest quantity, " the stratified masses<lb/>
are usually found most deranged and<lb/>
confused in their position.-<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Sections</del>
            <lb/>
Sketches of the sections of the strata will<lb/>
perhaps illustrate the History and a single<lb/>
glance of the eye will be more convincing<lb/>
than the most minute description -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instances</hi>
            <lb/>
It was in examining this curious<lb/>
phaenomena that Whitehurst was led<lb/>
to form the conclusion of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">connection</hi> of<lb/>
the disorder of the strata with the<lb/>
presence of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the <rs xml:id="ttag26" ref="#misc_855" type="miscellaneous">
                  <term xml:id="tag26">
          toadstone
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi> and finding<lb/>
that this rock was lower than the others<lb/>
and that no metalic veins existed in it<lb/>
and that even the veins of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag27">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
when intersected by it appeared on the<lb/>
opposite <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sides</hi> -<lb/>
He concluded that the strata were of<lb/>
prior formation and that this <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">substance</hi>
            <lb/>
had been interfused amongst them in<lb/>
a liquid state by some great convulsion<lb/>
of Nature. which had produced <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">chasms</del>
            <lb/>
chasms capable of receiving it and<lb/>
which had broken and dislodged the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag28">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag29" ref="#chemical_398" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag29">
          slate
          
        </term>
               </rs> and <rs xml:id="ttag30" ref="#chemical_090" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag30">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>.<lb/>
The <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag31"
                ref="#misc_855"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag31">
          toadstone
        </term>
            </rs> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag32"
                ref="#place_085"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag32" type="place">
          Derbyshire
        </name>
            </rs> and the<lb/>
lava of Vesuvius and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag33"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag33" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
            </rs> are very<lb/>
similar in many of their external<lb/>
properties -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
This resemblance did not escape Whitehurst<lb/>
and it afforded him new ideas and new analogies<lb/>
Lava is certainly formed by the action of<lb/>
Heat upon rock concealed in the very<lb/>
bosom of the Earth.-<lb/>
And it immediately occurred to our author<lb/>
that <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag34"
                ref="#misc_855"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag34">
          toadstone
        </term>
            </rs> must have had a similar origin<lb/>
and when He had conceived this his explana<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">tion</add>
            <lb/>
appeared complete: for it was easy to conceive<lb/>
that the same Volcanic fire which produced<lb/>
the ignited and liquid mass would be<lb/>
fully adequate to the derangement of the<lb/>
strata to the seperation of veins and<lb/>
to the formation of caverns in the<lb/>
superincumbent mass.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
All the facts seemed to combine all were<lb/>
subservient to one <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">demonstration</hi>.<lb/>
Fully satisfied with the truth of his<lb/>
early speculations with there apparent<lb/>
conformity to Nature:<lb/>
Whitehurst did not long suffer his imagination<lb/>
to rest upon the first aspect of things<lb/>
how objects of disruption arose new elucidation<lb/>
of them and partial Theory gradually<lb/>
led to general Hypotheses.-<lb/>
Most of the stratified Rocks of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag35"
                ref="#place_085"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag35" type="place">
          Derbyshire
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
contain shells or the remains of marine<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">animals</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
In considering this circumstance Whitehurst<lb/>
was led to form the conclusion almost<lb/>
common to Scientific Men that they had<lb/>
been covered by the Sea:<lb/>
And he immediately connected the cause<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">deluge</hi> with their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">present elevation</hi>
            <lb/>
supposing that they had been raised<lb/>
from the bottom of the ocean by the<lb/>
same fires which He conceived to<lb/>
have produced their irregularities.-<lb/>
During the rise of new continents<lb/>
and islands assumed to have taken place<lb/>
it necessarily follows that the waters<lb/>
must have flowed in upon the lands already<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">existing.</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="22"
                xml:id="pb-22"
                facs="#i22"/>
            <lb/>
And from so great a change in the surface<lb/>
the Author conceives that an alteration in<lb/>
the centre of gravity of the earth must<lb/>
have occurred and that in consequence<lb/>
at this period its axis may have gained<lb/>
its present inclination to the plane of<lb/>
its orbit.<lb/>
Such appear to have been the progress<lb/>
of the Mind of the philosopher of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag36"
                ref="#place_492"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag36" type="place">
          Derby
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
in his investigations.-<lb/>
Though in his work the results are<lb/>
stated in a different order. His reasonings<lb/>
are evidently all deduced from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">particular</hi>
            <lb/>
facts.<lb/>
But in develloping his system He<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="23"
                xml:id="pb-23"
                facs="#i23"/>
            <lb/>
commences with the statement of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">general</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">principles</hi> and He afterwards applies<lb/>
them to the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">phaenomena</hi>.-<lb/>
It will not be essential in our present<lb/>
enquiry to follow him minutely through<lb/>
the mere suppositions and extended parts<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag37"
                ref="#otherwork_322"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag37">
            of his Theory in which He reasons
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
concerning the creation and the original<lb/>
state of the Glove, a few words will<lb/>
sufficiently explain<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline"> his notions</hi>.-<lb/>
Guided by the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag38"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag38" type="person">
          Newtonian
        </name>
            </rs> Laws of Gravitation<lb/>
He ascertained that conceiving the earth<lb/>
to have been created as a fluid or soft<lb/>
mass it must have assumed on becoming<lb/>
solid the form which at present belong<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="24"
                xml:id="pb-24"
                facs="#i24"/>
            <lb/>
belongs to it that of an oblate spheroid<lb/>
flattened at the poles.-<lb/>
He supposes it to have been covered<lb/>
with water and peopled with marine<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">animals</hi> immediately after the creation<lb/>
and He conjectures that islands were<lb/>
gradually formed in the great ocean<lb/>
in consequence of the action of waves<lb/>
and currents which Islands He considers<lb/>
as the abodes of the antideluvian race<lb/>
of Men -<lb/>
He supposes like Burnet that before<lb/>
the deluge the Axis of the Earth was<lb/>
perpendicular to the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">P</del> plane of its orbit<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
and consequently that there was no variety<lb/>
of seasons and that days and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">nights were</hi>
            <lb/>
equal upon every part of the surface.-<lb/>
In his work a plate is given of the<lb/>
form of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primitive Islands</hi> raised<lb/>
at a gentle elevation from the sea<lb/>
This design <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">represents the Section</hi>
            <lb/>
These Islands the fancy of Whitehurst<lb/>
has pictured as abounding with all<lb/>
the richest productions of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi> as<lb/>
equally <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">free</add> from excess of Heat or Cold<lb/>
and as adapted in the best possible<lb/>
manner for the enjoyment of a life<lb/>
extended far beyond the present limits<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
of human existence and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">devoted</hi> to<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Peace </del>peace, to social &amp; domestic<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">useful <del rend="strikethrough">usefull</del> and refined pleasures</del>
            <lb/>
Happiness &amp; to pure &amp; refined enjoyment.-<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and to pure and <unclear>xxxxxxxx</unclear> delights</del>.-<lb/>
If any new arguments were wanting to<lb/>
prove the insufficency of human reason in its<lb/>
attempts at remote supposition and its inability<lb/>
to account minutely for the primeval state<lb/>
of things they might be derived from<lb/>
This conjectural history of the first period<lb/>
of the Globe.<lb/>
Whenever Whitehurst is directed by the<lb/>
arrangement of facts his ideas are always<lb/>
accurate and philosophical but when He<lb/>
enters the field of wild speculation his<lb/>
opinions are almost as visionary as those<lb/>
of the Elder Theorists<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
His account of the strata of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag39"
                ref="#place_085"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag39" type="place">
          Derbyshire
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
offers an admirable specimen of acute observation<lb/>
and plausible induction.<lb/>
It is on of the earliest and one of the most<lb/>
perfect of true Geological sketches - On the<lb/>
contrary, his Theories of primitive Islands<lb/>
and of the perpendicularity of the axis<lb/>
of the Earth are mere ingenious dreams.<lb/>
He endeavours indeed to show their conformi<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ty</add>
            <lb/>
to reason, and to sacred History <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">but without</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">success</hi>.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">And even allowing his conjectures</del> if<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the land had been distributed wholly</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in Islands over the ocean and if there</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">were no changes of seasons there is reason</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to believe that the general temperature</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the Globe would be lower than it</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">is at the present time</hi>
            </del>
            <lb/>
For the oblique rays of the Sun in<lb/>
the period of twelve hours could scarcely<lb/>
possess any effect upon the poles;<lb/>
ice in consequence would probably<lb/>
be continually accumulating there would<lb/>
be no extensive winds which are produced<lb/>
only by <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the</add> ascent of columns of Air from<lb/>
heated tracts of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Land</hi> of considerable<lb/>
extent; and which are necessary for<lb/>
blending the parts of the Atmosphere<lb/>
together and for equalizating their<lb/>
temperature.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
The lower strata of the air would<lb/>
in consequence soon become impure<lb/>
and unfit for the purposes of life -<lb/>
And on these ideas allowing the<lb/>
Hypotheses the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag40"
                ref="#misc_853"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag40">
          Antediluvians
        </term>
            </rs> instead of<lb/>
being gently warmed by a perpetual<lb/>
summer would have been chilled by<lb/>
the frosts of an eternal winter -<lb/>
Instead of breathing a purer and<lb/>
more etherial fluid they would have<lb/>
been exposed to an atmosphere filled<lb/>
with noxious and suffocating vapours.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
Animated Nature would have fallen rapidly<lb/>
into decay; and there would have been<lb/>
the established principle of reproduction<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">similar to that which exists in the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">present intelligent and harmonious order</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of things:</del>
            <lb/>
"new sheet"<lb/>
|_The system of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag41"
                ref="#person_520"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag41" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> de Luc
        </name>
            </rs> as it first<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag42"
                ref="#otherwork_323"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag42">
            made its appearance 1779
        </bibl>
            </rs> embraces a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">smaler</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">smaller</add>
            <lb/>
number of objects than that of Whitehurst<lb/>
but his discussions are more minute and<lb/>
his observations more general and extensive<lb/>
Whitehurst examined with attention<lb/>
the facts that were presented to him:<lb/>
but his sphere of observation was<lb/>
unfortunately limited to a particular<lb/>
district and He was unacquainted<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
with the greatest and most important<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mountain chains </hi>belonging to<lb/>
the Globe.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag43"
                ref="#person_520"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag43" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> de Luc
        </name>
            </rs> a native of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag44"
                ref="#place_198"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag44" type="place">
          Switzerland
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
from his infancy had been accustomed<lb/>
to the contemplation of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">magnificent</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">grandest</add>
            <lb/>
&amp; most elevated of the Mountain chains.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Rock scenery of <hi rend="underline">the <rs xml:id="ttag45" ref="#place_247" type="place">
                     <name xml:id="tag45" type="place">
          Alps
        </name>
                  </rs>
               </hi>
            </del>
            <lb/>
of Europe -<lb/>
He studied these great and interesting<lb/>
masses with attention and was enabled to<lb/>
compare the Geological phaenomena presented<lb/>
by them with similar phaenomena in<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag46"
                ref="#place_324"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag46" type="place">
          Germany
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag47"
                ref="#place_897"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag47" type="place">
          France 
        </name>
            </rs>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and <rs xml:id="ttag48" ref="#place_121" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag48" type="place">
          England
        </name>
               </rs>.</hi>.-<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag49"
                ref="#otherwork_323"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag49">
            In his letters to the Queen
        </bibl>
            </rs> facts are<lb/>
recorded with a truly philosophical spirit<lb/>
and his hypotheses are generally <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">advanced</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="32"
                xml:id="pb-32"
                facs="#i32"/>
            <lb/>
with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">diffidence </hi>and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">defended </hi>with moderation<lb/>
and candour.-<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag50"
                ref="#person_520"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag50" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> De Luc</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> commences his enquiries<lb/>
concerning Theory at the Mosaic account<lb/>
of the Creation He assumes a certain<lb/>
arrangement of things which He calls<lb/>
primordial and which He considers as<lb/>
resulting from the immediate will of<lb/>
the Almighty -<lb/>
He supposes that the surface of the<lb/>
Globe at its first formation contained<lb/>
a number <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and</del> of irregular and<lb/>
extensive caverns which were equally<lb/>
extended beneath the bed of the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="33"
                xml:id="pb-33"
                facs="#i33"/>
            <lb/>
Ocean and below the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Islands and</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">continents</hi>.-<lb/>
He refers the deluge to the destruction<lb/>
of these caverns by subterraneous fires<lb/>
and he supposes that at the time<lb/>
of this great convulsion of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi>
            <lb/>
the primeval <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">lands</hi> were broken down<lb/>
and covered by the Ocean which rushed<lb/>
into the abyss that they had overspread<lb/>
and that the present Islands and<lb/>
continents which before existed in the<lb/>
water were inconsequence uncovered<lb/>
so that the places of the land and<lb/>
sea were altogether changed.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="34"
                xml:id="pb-34"
                facs="#i34"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag51"
                ref="#person_520"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag51" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> de Luc
        </name>
            </rs> conceives that the Rocks which<lb/>
contain no organic remains and which<lb/>
form the bases and the summits of our<lb/>
highest mountains were parts of the<lb/>
primordial matter of the Globe -<lb/>
The stratified Rocks containing shells<lb/>
He regards as formed at the bottom<lb/>
of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag52"
                ref="#misc_853"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag52">
          antediluvian
        </term>
            </rs> ocean and the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag53"
                ref="#chemical_105"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag53">
          basaltic
          
        </term>
            </rs> Rocks which so often occur<lb/>
contiguous to the common stratified<lb/>
Rocks He considers as produced by<lb/>
marine Volcanoes.-<lb/>
In his first speculations the<lb/>
philosopher of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag54"
                ref="#place_226"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag54" type="place">
          Geneva
        </name>
            </rs> made no<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="35"
                xml:id="pb-35"
                facs="#i35"/>
            <lb/>
attempt to explain the minute parts<lb/>
of cosmogony.<lb/>
And He entered upon no discussions<lb/>
concerning the composition of the Chaos<lb/>
of the laws of its arrangement.<lb/>
In his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">later writings</hi> he appears<lb/>
however to have been reduced by too<lb/>
ardent a desire of Generalization<lb/>
And when He considers a confused<lb/>
fluid in which all things were <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">dissolved</del>
            <lb/>
dissolved as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the first</hi> form of our <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Globe</del>
            <lb/>
Globe and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">light</hi> as the principle<lb/>
which seperated its parts and gave<lb/>
to them regularity and order: and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="36"
                xml:id="pb-36"
                facs="#i36"/>
            <lb/>
when He regards this light as different<lb/>
from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the solar light</hi> it is impossible<lb/>
to follow with pleasure the wandering<lb/>
of his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">imagination</hi> it is impossible<lb/>
not to express a wish, that He<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">had rather</hi> confined his active and<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">powerful Genius</hi> to observations and<lb/>
to reasonings upon probabilities<lb/>
than have suffered it to waste its<lb/>
strength in vain attempts to penetrate<lb/>
into mystries which have been wisely<lb/>
concealed from Man and the Knowledge<lb/>
of which even if it could be obtained<lb/>
would be comparatively useless.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="37"
                xml:id="pb-37"
                facs="#i37"/>
            <lb/>
New leaf<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag55"
                ref="#otherwork_324"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag55">
            |_The system of the Earth
        </bibl>
            </rs> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag56"
                ref="#person_1063"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag56" type="person">
          Wallerius
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
agrees in many of its points with<lb/>
that of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag57"
                ref="#person_520"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag57" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> De Luc</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> it is less valuable<lb/>
as containing more Hypotheses and<lb/>
less of observation:<lb/>
The learned swedish professor who<lb/>
followed the steps of the celebrated<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag58"
                ref="#person_247"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag58" type="person">
          Linnaeus
        </name>
            </rs> in attempting to produce an<lb/>
accurate <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">class</del> classification of minerals<lb/>
has not been very successful in his<lb/>
efforts to apply a sound understanding<lb/>
fitted for the arrangement of facts to<lb/>
conjecture and analogical conclusions<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="38"
                xml:id="pb-38"
                facs="#i38"/>
            <lb/>
He founds an important part of<lb/>
this Theory upon the same basis as<lb/>
Whitehurst that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perpendicularity</hi> of the<lb/>
axis <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Earth</hi> to the plane of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">its orbit before the deluge</hi>; and<lb/>
He conceives that the inclination<lb/>
of the axis was the first cause of<lb/>
the inundation of the waters which<lb/>
broke down and destroyed the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">land</hi>
            <lb/>
He reasons much more upon the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primordial</hi> state of things than upon<lb/>
their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">present arrangement</hi>and his<lb/>
ideas concerning the first forms of<lb/>
Matter are very little connected with<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="39"
                xml:id="pb-39"
                facs="#i39"/>
            <lb/>
established phaenomena.-<lb/>
A very interesting account of this<lb/>
Theory may be found in M<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag59"
                ref="#person_151"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag59" type="person">
          Howards
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag60"
                ref="#otherwork_325"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag60">
            Letters on the scriptural History of<lb/>the Globe:
        </bibl>
            </rs> a work which excepting<lb/>
the hypothetical parts is filled with<lb/>
much useful and curious information<lb/>
and which contains some beautiful<lb/>
views of the alterations of the<lb/>
Globe at present taking place -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">New leaf</hi>
            <lb/>
|_A short time after the system of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag61"
                ref="#person_1063"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag61" type="person">
          Wallerius
        </name>
            </rs> had been <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">brought forward</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag62"
                ref="#otherwork_097"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag62">
            The Theory of the Earth of D<hi rend="superscript">r </hi> Hutton
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
made its first appearance <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">)</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="40"
                xml:id="pb-40"
                facs="#i40"/>
            <lb/>
And this period may be almost considered<lb/>
as forming an era in the History of<lb/>
Geology.<lb/>
Few works have ever excited more<lb/>
attention few works have been more warmly<lb/>
admired or more vehemently <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">attacked</hi>
            <lb/>
and it has at least answered the<lb/>
important <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of</del> end of keeping the<lb/>
public interest alive to the facts<lb/>
and discoveries of the Science.-<lb/>
Many of the Elements of it may be<lb/>
found in the writings of preceding<lb/>
Authors in those of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag63"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag63" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag64"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag64" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and particularly of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag65"
                ref="#person_303"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag65" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Lazaro More</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> who<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="41"
                xml:id="pb-41"
                facs="#i41"/>
            <lb/>
supposed all Mountains to have been<lb/>
formed by Volcanic <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mountains</del> eruptions<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag66"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag66" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> however in cases when He<lb/>
has borrowed materials has given to<lb/>
them a new and more philosophical<lb/>
arrangement: and He has combined<lb/>
them in such a manner with the<lb/>
result of his own observations and<lb/>
his own reflections as to form a whole<lb/>
in which all the parts are well<lb/>
adapted <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to each other</hi> and though it<lb/>
is easy to doubt of the truth of the<lb/>
system it is scarcely possible not to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="42"
                xml:id="pb-42"
                facs="#i42"/>
            <lb/>
admire the order and ingenuity with<lb/>
which it is contrived.-<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag67"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag67" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> reasoning like <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag68"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag68" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
conceives that the agency of the<lb/>
atmosphere and of water must<lb/>
occasion the mountains of the Earth<lb/>
constantly to diminish and He<lb/>
supposes that a time must arrive in<lb/>
the lapse of ages when all the<lb/>
solid land which constitutes our<lb/>
present continents and Islands must<lb/>
be wholly destroyed by the agency<lb/>
of Rivers and carried into the depths<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the ocean</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="43"
                xml:id="pb-43"
                facs="#i43"/>
            <lb/>
From such a cause He shews that the<lb/>
order of Nature must be wholly destroyed<lb/>
if there did not exist another cause Capable<lb/>
of renovating the land and of opposing<lb/>
the agency of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water</hi> -<lb/>
This cause He considers <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">as fire</hi> acting<lb/>
under the pressure of the sea and<lb/>
He attempts to prove that in the cycle<lb/>
of events the solid Earth that we<lb/>
at present <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">inhabit</hi> had been formed by<lb/>
fusion at the bottom of a former Ocean<lb/>
and raised from it by igneous explosion<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag69"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag69" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> attempts to support his system by<lb/>
numerous appeals to observation &amp; to experience<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="44"
                xml:id="pb-44"
                facs="#i44"/>
            <lb/>
He quotes a variety of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">instances</hi> in<lb/>
which rocks have been observed to<lb/>
diminish in which the beds of rivers<lb/>
have become deeper and in which<lb/>
the ocean has gained upon <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the land</hi>
            <lb/>
He details the history of the elevation<lb/>
of various Islands in the midst of<lb/>
the ocean by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">submarine volcanoes</hi>
            <lb/>
And assuming the production of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag70" ref="#chemical_105" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag70">
          Basalt
          
        </term>
               </rs> by fire,</hi>
            <lb/>
He attempts to shew that there<lb/>
exists a strong analogy between this<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="45"
                xml:id="pb-45"
                facs="#i45"/>
            <lb/>
substance <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and <rs xml:id="ttag71" ref="#chemical_092" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag71">
          Granite
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi> and that the<lb/>
mixture <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of <rs xml:id="ttag72" ref="#chemical_105" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag72">
          Basalt
          
        </term>
               </rs> with</hi> the Rocks<lb/>
containing organic remains bears a<lb/>
strong analogy to the intersection of<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primordial</hi> or primitive Rocks<lb/>
by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">veins</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag73"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag73">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
|_The two Theories that have been<lb/>
most opposed to that of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag74"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag74" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> have<lb/>
been the invention of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag75"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag75" type="person">
          Professor <hi rend="underline">Werner</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag76"
                ref="#person_023"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag76" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Kirwan
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
In the Geognosy of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag77"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag77" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> water is<lb/>
made the great agent both of decompositi<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">on</add>
            <lb/>
and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of formation</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="46"
                xml:id="pb-46"
                facs="#i46"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag78"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag78" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> conceives that in the beginning<lb/>
of things all the existing substances<lb/>
composing the Globe were in a state<lb/>
of solution by the aqueous fluid.<lb/>
And He assumes that in consequence<lb/>
of the law of chemical attraction<lb/>
and in consequence of the polarity<lb/>
of the particles; they assumed the<lb/>
forms that at present belong to them<lb/>
The Rocks that are called primord<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ial</add>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">or primitive</hi> and that contain no<lb/>
organic remains He supposes the first<lb/>
to have been deposited from the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="47"
                xml:id="pb-47"
                facs="#i47"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">original</hi> aqueous solution, and he<lb/>
considers them as the result of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">chrystalization</hi> and of an arrangement<lb/>
of Matter in which all attractive<lb/>
powers were duly opposed to each other.<lb/>
After <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the first</hi> production of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Rocks</hi> from the<lb/>
dissolving <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fluid</hi> He supposes counterballancing<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">opposites</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">affinities</add> in consequence of which certain substances<lb/>
before dissolved were <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">thrown down</hi> not in the<lb/>
chrystalized form but rather in a state of<lb/>
Mechanical division and from their mixture<lb/>
with the substances of primitive <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">formation</hi>
            <lb/>
He supposes a new class of Rocks which He<lb/>
calls the transitional Rocks to have been formed.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="48"
                xml:id="pb-48"
                facs="#i48"/>
            <lb/>
At the period of the deposition of the<lb/>
transitional Rocks <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag79"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag79" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> supposes the<lb/>
Ocean to have been peopled with living<lb/>
beings and hence He accounts for the shells<lb/>
and remains of Marine Animals existing<lb/>
in them.<lb/>
The last epoch in his Geology is the<lb/>
production of the secondary or highly stratified<lb/>
Masses containing <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in almost all their parts</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">organic remains</hi> and these He conjectures<lb/>
to have been produced wholly by the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Mechanical</hi> precipitation of the lowest<lb/>
solid materials which had been suspended<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in the ocean</hi> and which the former<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="49"
                xml:id="pb-49"
                facs="#i49"/>
            <lb/>
depositions had rendered free so as to make<lb/>
them to be thrown down <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in regular strata</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with the decomposing materials of the animated</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">beings belonging to the Sea</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag80"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag80" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> perhaps more than any other<lb/>
man has had opportunities of observing the<lb/>
facts of Geology belonging to a particular<lb/>
district in their most minute and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">abstruse</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">relations</hi> from his situation as professor<lb/>
of Mineralogy in the School of Mines at<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag81"
                ref="#place_991"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag81" type="place">
          Friburg
        </name>
            </rs> the greatest perhaps ever established<lb/>
He has been enabled to inspect the<lb/>
most important of the forms in which<lb/>
the varieties of subterraneous bodies are<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="50"
                xml:id="pb-50"
                facs="#i50"/>
            <lb/>
presented to us.-<lb/>
And yet in theory He has contented<lb/>
himself with stating what He <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">himself</add> even considers<lb/>
as a mere History of guesses.<lb/>
He has allowed insurmountable difficulties<lb/>
in the way of a perfect arrangement and<lb/>
his cosmogony seems <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">rather</del> designed to<lb/>
satisfy the ardent imagination <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of students</hi>
            <lb/>
in Geology and to awaken the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">attention</hi>
            <lb/>
of Scholars <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">rather</add> than to communicate any<lb/>
accurate views of Nature or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to satisfy</hi>
            <lb/>
the wishes or desires of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">true Philosopher</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag82"
                ref="#person_023"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag82" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Kirwan
        </name>
            </rs> in his Geological essays<lb/>
has in many cases followed principles<lb/>
of reasoning similar <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to those adopted by</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="51"
                xml:id="pb-51"
                facs="#i51"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag83"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag83" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Werner</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
like the philosopher of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag84"
                ref="#place_991"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag84" type="place">
          Frigburg
        </name>
            </rs> He has<lb/>
supposed an universal aqueous solution<lb/>
of the solid materials of the Globe and<lb/>
he has accounted for their deposition in<lb/>
a similar manner:<lb/>
But He has in all cases endeavoured<lb/>
to adapt his own particular Theories to<lb/>
the sacred History of the creation and in<lb/>
consequence <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and</del> has often exposed himself<lb/>
to the imputation of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">erroneous </hi>interpretati<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">on</add>
            <lb/>
Thus when He considers the sublime<lb/>
passage "God said let their be light and<lb/>
there was light" as merely expressing<lb/>
the bursting forth of Volcanic fires<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="52"
                xml:id="pb-52"
                facs="#i52"/>
            <lb/>
in the arranging chaotic mass it is<lb/>
impossible not to suppose him mistaken<lb/>
And when He conjectures the sentence<lb/>
which states the the "Spirit of God<lb/>
moved upon the face of the waters<lb/>
merely <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">signify</del> to imply that a great<lb/>
evaporation took place from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Sea</hi>
            <lb/>
There is no sound reasoner who will<lb/>
not beleive the meaning <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to be forced</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and unsatisfactory</hi>.-<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#person_023"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag85" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Kirwan
        </name>
            </rs> has done much for Science<lb/>
As a Chemist his labours are always<lb/>
valuable, as a recorder of facts his<lb/>
statements are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">estimable</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="53"
                xml:id="pb-53"
                facs="#i53"/>
            <lb/>
In censuring his Geological opinions<lb/>
I censure only what may be considered<lb/>
as the lighter ebullitions of his fancy<lb/>
His productions on general philosophy<lb/>
are often deep and refined and always<lb/>
interesting and instructive His reputation<lb/>
has been <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">well and fully</hi> merited.<lb/>
And that he may long continue to enjoy<lb/>
that reputation must be the wish of<lb/>
every disinterested friend of true <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">philosophy</hi>
            <lb/>
|_Controversies between the Theorist who<lb/>
considered the present state of the Globe<lb/>
as resulting from the agency of fire;<lb/>
and those who regard it as the effect<lb/>
of the power of water, have been carried<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="54"
                xml:id="pb-54"
                facs="#i54"/>
            <lb/>
on with great <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ardor</hi>.<lb/>
And the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">two systems </hi>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">from</del> have<lb/>
been named in opposition to each<lb/>
other, the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag86"
                ref="#misc_100"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag86">
                  <hi rend="underline">Plutonic</hi>
               </term>
            </rs> and the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag87"
                ref="#misc_588"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag87">
                  <hi rend="underline">neptunian</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">systems</hi> from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag88" ref="#person_263" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag88" type="person">
          Pluto
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the god of subterranean fire </add>and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag89"
                ref="#misc_560"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag89">
                  <hi rend="underline">Neptune</hi>
               </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">The one supposed by the Greeks</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to be the titulary God of the subterranean</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">fires</hi> and the other the deity of the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">ocean</hi> and of water</del>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag90"
                ref="#otherwork_097"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag90">
            The<del rend="strikethrough">Hypotheses</del>
                  <add>Theory</add> of D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hutton
        </bibl>
            </rs> like that<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag91"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag91" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> and of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag92"
                ref="#person_023"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag92" type="person">
          Kirwan
        </name>
            </rs> has been principally<lb/>
founded upon <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">conjectures </hi>-<lb/>
For as yet there have been no<lb/>
positive proofs that the principal materials<lb/>
of our Globe are either soluble in water<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="55"
                xml:id="pb-55"
                facs="#i55"/>
            <lb/>
or capable of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">being fused by fire and</hi>
            <lb/>
deposited in regular forms in consequence<lb/>
of cooling.-<lb/>
The masterly experiments of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag93"
                ref="#person_164"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag93" type="person">
          Sir James<lb/>Hall
        </name>
            </rs> have indeed <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">shewn</hi> that <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag94"
                ref="#chemical_105"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag94">
          Basalt
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
rendered fluid in our furnaces may be<lb/>
chrystalized by a slow diminution of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">temperature</hi> and that <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag95"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag95">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs> may be<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">rendered fluid</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">fused <unclear>xxxx</unclear>
            </add> under great pressure<lb/>
without loosing any of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">fixed air</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">or <rs xml:id="ttag96" ref="#chemical_058" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag96">
          Carbonic Acid
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <rs xml:id="ttag97" ref="#chemical_078" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag97">
          elastic fluid
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </add> with which it is combined<lb/>
But no strong analogies can be applied<lb/>
from these most interesting facts, to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag98" ref="#chemical_092" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag98">
          Granite
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
to the regularly formed gems or to any<lb/>
of the perfectly aggregated Rocks<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="56"
                xml:id="pb-56"
                facs="#i56"/>
            <lb/>
containg no organic remains.-<lb/>
The general theory is almost as<lb/>
obscure as before, the early operations<lb/>
of Nature are unknown<lb/>
And the laws of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">formation</hi> of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">habitable Globe</hi> are still <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">almost</add> as little<lb/>
understood as those of the production<lb/>
of the general planetary system<lb/>
of the Sun and of the fixed stars<lb/>
We are informed <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">by</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag99"
                ref="#person_1064"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag99" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Clemens</hi>
                  <add>Alexandinus</add>
               </name>
            </rs> that the<lb/>
Egyptian Priests <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">Alexandrinus</hi>
            </del> made a<lb/>
statue of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag100"
                ref="#misc_783"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag100">
          God Serapis
        </term>
            </rs> in which<lb/>
they blended together all the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">known</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Metals</hi> all the stones <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and all the soil</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="57"
                xml:id="pb-57"
                facs="#i57"/>
            <lb/>
commonly found in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag101"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag101" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs> / and this statue<lb/>
has been supposed to represent the<lb/>
primordial state of things.<lb/>
A useful lesson at least may be derived<lb/>
from the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">narrative</hi>.-<lb/>
No person uninstructed in the history<lb/>
supposing the image now existing would<lb/>
be able to reason from the form concernin<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">g</add>
            <lb/>
the materials, and no person from viewing<lb/>
the materials would be able to devellope<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the <del rend="strikethrough">means</del>
            </hi> by which they <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">were designed</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">were mingled</add>
            <lb/>
or the end for which they were designed.<lb/>
The powers of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Man are scanty and</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">definite</hi> even the origins of certain<lb/>
well known human <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">productions</hi> are<lb/>
far beyond the power of his investigation<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="58"
                xml:id="pb-58"
                facs="#i58"/>
            <lb/>
He is unable satisfactorily to explain<lb/>
the erection of the pyramids of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag102"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag102" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs> of of the Druidical pillars of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag103"
                ref="#place_1316"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag103" type="place">
          Stonehenge.-
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
And yet he is sufficiently daring<lb/>
to endeavour to apply his mind to<lb/>
the most operations which have<lb/>
been produced by divine intelligence<lb/>
to attempt <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to explain</hi> the changes<lb/>
that have taken place beneath the<lb/>
foundations of the Earth:<lb/>
to examine the great laws of the<lb/>
creation of the systems of the<lb/>
universe and to reason concerning<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="59"
                xml:id="pb-59"
                facs="#i59"/>
            <lb/>
Their origin in that infinite space<lb/>
which he is wholly unable to <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">penetra<add>te</add>
            </del>
            <lb/>
penetrate or even accurately to imagine.<lb/>
As I have spoken of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag104"
                ref="#otherwork_097"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag104">
            Theories of D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  <lb/>Hutton
        </bibl>
            </rs> and M<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag105"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag105" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> it would be<lb/>
unjust If I passed over <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">without noticing</hi>
            <lb/>
the later important Geological<lb/>
publication.<lb/>
The elucidations of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag106"
                ref="#otherwork_097"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag106">
            Huttonian<lb/>Theory
        </bibl>
            </rs> by Professor <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag107" ref="#person_162" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag107" type="person">
          Playfair
        </name>
               </rs>:</hi>.-<lb/>
In this excellent work the ideas of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag108"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag108" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">develloped</hi> with precision<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and beauty</hi> and an arrangement<lb/>
is given to them infinitely superior<lb/>
to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that exhibited by the original Author</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="60"
                xml:id="pb-60"
                facs="#i60"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag109"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag109" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> is obscure and perplexed<lb/>
from the multitude of facts which<lb/>
crowded on his mind.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag110"
                ref="#person_162"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag110" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Fairplay
        </name>
            </rs> gifted with the faculty<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of selection</hi> has discriminated such<lb/>
phaenomena only as are calculated to<lb/>
elucidate <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">his opinions</hi> -<lb/>
He has given <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to the plutonian</hi> Theory<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">a new a more</hi> philosophical and a<lb/>
more fascinating form.<lb/>
And whatever may be the fate of the<lb/>
opinions of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag111"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag111" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton
        </name>
            </rs> the work of<lb/>
the distinguished Professor of Natural<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="61"
                xml:id="pb-61"
                facs="#i61"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">philosophy of <rs xml:id="ttag112" ref="#place_284" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag112" type="place">
          Edinburgh
        </name>
               </rs> considered</del>
            <lb/>
philosophy <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of <rs xml:id="ttag113" ref="#place_284" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag113" type="place">
          Edinburgh
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> considered as<lb/>
a literary production will stand the<lb/>
ordeal of time and of the most rigid<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">criticism</hi>.-<lb/>
The elegance and accuracy <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of his</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">declamation</hi> must be always applauded<lb/>
and the precision and clearness of his<lb/>
method and of his style will constantly<lb/>
be subjects of admiration.-<lb/>
In the investigation of Geology as<lb/>
in almost all other enquiries to which<lb/>
the human mind has been ardently<lb/>
devoted very few speculations have<lb/>
indeed been formed not possessed of some<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="62"
                xml:id="pb-62"
                facs="#i62"/>
            <lb/>
immediate or remote applications to<lb/>
the real progress of Science.-<lb/>
The understanding is permanently<lb/>
guided by experience:<lb/>
And Brilliant delusions even though<lb/>
consecrated by the efforts of genius<lb/>
cannot very long continue to deceive the<lb/>
public.<lb/>
Useful truths are often ascertained in<lb/>
the attempts made to detect imposing<lb/>
errors:<lb/>
And the appeal to experiment which<lb/>
is the last and the only certain test<lb/>
of the merits of opinion can hardly<lb/>
fail to lead to discovery.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="63"
                xml:id="pb-63"
                facs="#i63"/>
            <lb/>
Hypothesis uniformly produces <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">discussion</hi>
            <lb/>
and the more ingenious and the<lb/>
more active the talents by which it<lb/>
was formed the greater is the probabil<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ity</add>
            <lb/>
of a minute and serious examination<lb/>
of facts.-<lb/>
To explain Nature and the laws<lb/>
instituted by the Author of Nature<lb/>
and to apply the phaenomena presented<lb/>
in the external World to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">useful</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">purposes</hi> are the great ends of<lb/>
physical investigation and these ends<lb/>
can only be obtained by the exertion<lb/>
of all the faculties of the mind.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="64"
                xml:id="pb-64"
                facs="#i64"/>
            <lb/>
And the imagination the memory<lb/>
and the reason are perhaps equally<lb/>
essential to the devellopement of<lb/>
great and important truths.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="65"
                xml:id="pb-65"
                facs="#i65"/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="66"
                xml:id="pb-66"
                facs="#i66"/>
            <lb/>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
